Lab 7.8.2 - Splines

~Overview of Regression Splines~ Regression splines are piecewise polynomial regressionn, which involves fitting several low-degree polynomials over different regions of X. We use knots to separate the regions, say K knots, which means that we will have K+1 different polynomials for regressions. In general, more knots represent higher flexibility of piecewise polynomials. While we are trying to better fit the data, constraints are also necessary to avoid the discontinuity of the fitted curve. Overall, in order to do regression splines, we need to specify a set of knots, produce a sequence of basis functions, and then use least squares to estimate the spline coefficients. However, as the function becomes far less flexible, i.e. it overfits the data, we need to “smooth” the function, that is, to minimize the second derivative of functions.

In order to run a Regression Spline in R, we use the splines library. Regression splines can be fit by constructing an appropriate matrix of basis functions denoted by bs(). This function generates the entire matrix of basis functions for splines with the specified set of knots, and the default is cubic splines.

Below is an example of fitting wage to age using a regression spline:

library(splines)
agelims = range(age)
age.grid = seq(from = agelims[1], to=agelims[2])
fit=lm(wage~bs(age,knots=c(25,40,60)),data=Wage)
pred=predict(fit,newdata=list(age=age.grid),se=T)

We have prespecified knots at ages 25, 40, and 60. This produces a spline with six basic functions.

The following plots the regression spline:

plot(age,wage,col="gray")
lines(age.grid,pred$fit,lwd=2)
lines(age.grid,pred$fit+2*pred$se,lty="dashed")
lines(age.grid,pred$fit-2*pred$se,lty="dashed")

dim(bs(age,knots=c(25,40,60)))
## [1] 3000    6

We could also use the df option to produce a spline with knots at uniform quantiles of the data. Here we have chosen six degrees of freedom.

dim(bs(age,df=6))
## [1] 3000    6
attr(bs(age,df=6),"knots")
##   25%   50%   75% 
## 33.75 42.00 51.00

In this case R chooses knots at ages 33.75, 42.00, and 51.00 which correspond to the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles of age.Also, the bs() function has a degree argument, so we can fit splines of any degree, rather than the default degree of 3 (which yields a cubic spline).

~Overview of Natural Splines~

In order to fit a natural spline, we use the ns() function. The below function fits a natural spline with four degrees of freedom.

fit2=lm(wage~ns(age,df=4),data=Wage)
pred2=predict(fit2,newdata=list(age=age.grid),se=T)
plot(age,wage,xlim=agelims,cex=.5,col="darkgrey")
title("Natural Spline")
lines(age.grid, pred2$fit,col="red",lwd=2)
lines(age.grid, pred2$fit+2*pred2$se,col = 'red', lty="dashed")
lines(age.grid, pred2$fit-2*pred2$se,col = 'red', lty="dashed")

Similarly to the bs() function, we can instead specify the knots directly if we wish.

Overview of Smoothing Splines ~

In order to fit a smoothing spline, we use the smooth.spline() function.

plot(age,wage,xlim=agelims,cex=.5,col="darkgrey")
title("Smoothing Spline")
fit=smooth.spline(age,wage,df=16)
fit2=smooth.spline(age,wage,cv=TRUE)
fit2$df
## [1] 6.794596
lines(fit,col="red",lwd=2)
lines(fit2,col="blue",lwd=2)
legend("topright",legend=c("16 DF","6.8 DF"),col=c("red","blue"),lty=1,lwd=2,cex=.8)

Notice that in the first call to smooth.spline(), we specified degrees of freedom to 16. In the second call, we select the smoothness level by cross-validation, and this results in a value of lambda that yields 6.8 degrees of freedom.

Overview of local regression ~

In order to perform local regression, we use the loess() function.

plot(age,wage,xlim=agelims,cex=.5,col="darkgrey")
title("Local Regression")
fit=loess(wage~age,span=.2,data=Wage)
fit2=loess(wage~age,span=.5,data=Wage)
lines(age.grid,predict(fit,data.frame(age=age.grid)),col="red",lwd=2)
lines(age.grid,predict(fit2,data.frame(age=age.grid)),col="blue",lwd=2)
legend("topright",legend=c("Span=0.2","Span=0.5"),col=c("red","blue"),lty=1,lwd=2,cex=.8)

Here we have performed local linear regression using spans of 0.2 and 0.5, that is, each neighborhood consists of 20% or 50% of the observations. The larger the span, the smoother the fit.

Lab 7.8.3 - GAMs

~Overview of GAMS~ Generalized Additive Model extends a standard linear model by allowing non-linear functions, of each feature while still maintaining additivity. What’s good about GAMs is that it allows both numeric and categorical features.

Install the following packages for this lab:

library(gam)
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded gam 1.16.1
library(akima)

We fit a GAM to predict wage using natural spline functions of year and age, treating education as a qualitative predictor. Since this is just a big linear regression model using an appropriate choice of basis functions, we can simply use the lm() function for the gam1 model.

gam1=lm(wage~ns(year,4)+ns(age,5)+education,data=Wage)

For gam.m3, we fit the model using smoothing splines rather than natural splines. In order to fit more general sorts of GAMs, using smoothing splines or other components that cannot be expressed in terms of basis functions and then fit using least squares regression, we will need to use the gam library and call the gam() function.

gam.m3=gam(wage~s(year,4)+s(age,5)+education,data=Wage)

The s() function, which is part of the gam library, is used to indicate that we would like to use a smoothing spline. We specify that the function of year should have 4 degrees of freedom, and that the function of age will have 5 degrees of freedom. Since education is a qualitative variable, we leave it and it is converted into a dummy variable. The gam() function fits a GAM using these components simultaneously.

The generic plot() function recognizes that gam.m3 is an object of class gam, and invokes plot.Gam() method. Even though gam1 is not of class gam but rather of class lm, we can still use plot.Gam() on it.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(gam.m3, se=TRUE,col="blue")

plot.Gam(gam1, se=TRUE, col="red")

In these plots, the function year appears linear. We can perform a series of ANOVA tests in order to determine which of these three models is best: a GAM that excludes year (M1), a GAM that uses a linear function of year (M2), or a GAM that uses a spline function of year (M3).

gam.m1=gam(wage~s(age,5)+education,data=Wage)
gam.m2=gam(wage~year+s(age,5)+education,data=Wage)
anova(gam.m1,gam.m2,gam.m3,test="F")
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model 1: wage ~ s(age, 5) + education
## Model 2: wage ~ year + s(age, 5) + education

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We find that there is compelling evidence that a GAM with a linear function of year is better than a GAM that does not include year at all (note the p-value of 0.0001447). However, there is no evidence that a non-linear function of year is needed (p-value of 0.349). Therefore, we choose M2.

The large p-value of year found in the summary reinforces our conclusion from the ANOVA test that a linear function is adequate for this term. However, there is clear evidence that a non-linear term is required for age.

We can make predictions from gam objects, just like from lm objects, using the predict() method for the class gam. Below we make predictions on the training set.

preds=predict(gam.m2,newdata=Wage)

We can also use local regression fits as building blocks in a GAM, using the lo() function.

gam.lo=gam(wage~s(year,df=4)+lo(age,span=0.7)+education,data=Wage)
plot.Gam(gam.lo, se=TRUE, col="green")

Here we have used local regression for the age term, with a span of 0.7.

We can also use the lo() function to create interactions before calling the gam() function. The model gam.lo fits a two-term model, in which the first term is an interaction between year and age, fit be a local regression surface. We can plot the resulting 2-D surface if we first install the akima package.

gam.lo.i=gam(wage~lo(year,age,span=0.5)+education,data=Wage)
plot(gam.lo.i)

In order to fit a logistic regression GAM, we once again use the I() function in constructing the binary response variable, and set family=binomial.

gam.lr=gam(I(wage>250)~year+s(age,df=5)+education,family=binomial,data=Wage)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(gam.lr,se=T,col="green")

table(education,I(wage>250))
##                     
## education            FALSE TRUE
##   1. < HS Grad         268    0
##   2. HS Grad           966    5
##   3. Some College      643    7
##   4. College Grad      663   22
##   5. Advanced Degree   381   45

It is easy to see that there are no high earners in the <HS category. Hence, we fit a logistic regression GAM using all but this category. This provides more sensible results.

gam.lr.s=gam(I(wage>250)~year+s(age,df=5)+education,family=binomial,data=Wage,subset=(education!="1. < HS Grad"))
plot(gam.lr.s,se=T,col="green")
